As an introverted, privacy-conscious creative individual running my own business, it shouldn't feel so awkward, but sometimes it does. Most online resources and mentors tell you to be extroverted when dealing with large (evil) tech companies. Advertise here, follow the algorithms, share your charm. Get verified on that service, stay online all day, answer questions with your own videos, and respond immediately. Video, video, and more video.
1/3
This year has been a transition year for me.
I no longer want to dedicate my money, data, and energy to large tech companies, nor do I want to listen to mentors who only apply a single extroverted solution to everyone. I'm exploring new business models while also working to overcome my long-held belief that success can only be achieved by doing things in a certain specific way.
Good luck to me!
The first step has been taken.
I left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my personal WhatsApp account.
Yesterday, I also removed the last external tracker from my website - Google Analytics, and I felt great.
To better support GDPR, I recently subscribed to a European CRM service and will be migrating my business over there in the coming weeks.
I transferred my MX records to Proton and now have complete SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for basic email verification anymore.
3/3
